-o+o\nRICHARD GILES\nWAS RELEASED\nRichard Giles, the negro who sbo;\nand killed Louis McPherson, anoth\ner negro, at the home of Nancy\nMoyer, a negress, on West Fourth\navenue, Wednesday night, was yes\nterday relased, the coroner\u2019s jury\ndeciding that his act was justifiable\nThe story told to Coroner R. D\nMcGaughy and his jurors by wit\nnesses was the same as that relatec\nin the Graphic Thursday morning\nIt seems that McPherson, who wa:\narmed with a Winchester rifle, at\ntempted to enter the Moyer worn\nan\u2019s homo with the intention o\nshooting either Giles, the womar\nor both of them. A .bullet from\nrevolver in the hands of Giles stop\n,ped him. The coroner\u2019s jury tlmr\noughly investigated the matter am\nreturned a verdict of justifiabl\nhomicide.\nThe Young Ladies Club of th.\nFirst Methodist church will meet a\n3 o\u2019clock Saturday afternoon witl\nMiss Moree Burks at the residence\nof her sister, Mrs. M. C. Cleveland\non East Sixth avenue.\n4\nt n t 4\n\u2022a it,'.- X-T i.'\niwwi\u2014wiiiiiwiiiiihi'iiiiiii 'irrr\nI\nA LOCAL MODEL\nLICENSE LEAGUE\nOrganized in This City Last Night by Wholesale and\nRetail Liquor Dealers\u2014They Will Demand That the\nLaws Be Obeyed by Saloon Men State Convention\nto Be Held in Little Rock\u2014Objects of the League.\nA meeting was lieltl ai the Hotel\nI Jefferson in Ibis city last night l)y nil\nthe local wholesale and retail dealers\n(for the purpose of organizing a local\nModel License League, which will be\nan auxiliary of the national body of\nthat name. The meeting was called\nby E. J. Hutson, of Louisville, Ky..\nthe national organizer, who arrived\nhere yestq^day from Memphis, where\na similar organization with a large\nmembership was recently perfected.\nThe meeting was largely attended by\nthe representative liquor men of the\ncity and much interest was displayed\nin the proposed organization. The ob\njects of the league and its local work\nwas unanimously endorsed and agreed\nupon by them. T. E. Buck was elected\ntemporary chairman and Harry Ilanf,\nsecretary. It is proposed to effect per\nmanent organization after a State con\nvention, which is to be held in Little\nRock within the next ten days. :S. F.\nRosenberg, J. W .Vilen and W. E. Dud\nj ley were named as a committee to\n''visit every liquor man in this city to\nday with a view of getting them to\nagree to obey every law now standing\nupon the statute books with reference\nto the liquor traffic. This involves the\nnecessity of closing when the law says\nthey shall and remaining closed when\nthe law requires. This and the re\nmoval of the saloon from politics rep\nresents the keynote of the national\nModel League movement.\nIn discussing the objects of the\nleague last night Mr. Hutson said:\n\u201cI tohl the gentlemen present that we\nwere meeting with one object in view,\nand that was for our mutual benefit\nand also for the benefit of society at\nlarge. I told them that we had noth\ning to conceal and that we had the\nunited support of newspapers all over\nthe United States and that it had been\nfound to our advantage to at all times\npermit newspaper men to be present\nat our meetings.\n\u201cI explained to them that we were\nconfronted with a terrific proposition,\nthat unless we immediately took steps\nto satisfy the demands being made by\na large element in society for liquor\nregulation, that our business was ab\nsolutely doomed. 1 explained to them\nthat our trade represented an invest\nREAL ESTATE\nTRANSFERS\nReported Daily by\nT. ROBERTS SON,\nAbstracters of Titles and Real\nEstate.\nNo. 113 Main Street.\n>Y :Jt :<t\nFred Wilson and wife and W. E.\nHendrick and wife to M. Danaher,\ndeed of trust, $1,000; pt uw 1-4 nw\n1-4 sw. 15, 6, 0.\nW. S. Young to Mrs. H. .1. Clem\nmons, admx., deed of trust, l,\n096.56; e 1-2 uw 1-4, nw 1-4 nw\n1-4 sec. 30 and sw 1-4 sec. 19. 7, 6.\n.1. M. liousen and wife to Anita\nK. T'ltompson, deed of trust, $464;\nsw 1-4 blk 35, Harding\u2019s add.\nM. K. Uowson, Garrett llowson\nand wife to Citizens bank, deed of\ntrust, $1 S.000; \"Clayton I\u2019lace.\n,1. II. Core and wife to Beulah\nSennett, deed of trust, $3,000; pt\n01 4, blk 17. James\u2019 tuld.\nE. M. Wilson and Fred Wilson to\nW. N. Trulock, deed of trust, $1.\n000; lots S and 9, blk 16, M. .1.\nScull\u2019s add.\nNellie Harris to Charlie Jones,\nwarranty deed, $90; lot 3 and vs 1-2\nlot 2. blk 20 of J. W. Monk\u2019s add.\nCornelia Thompson to Isaac New\nton, warrany deed. $700; sc 1-1 sr\n1-4 sec. 12. 7, 7.\nTRANSCRIPT FILED\nIN RICHIE CASE\nThe transcript in the case of t it\ni State of Arkansas against E. C.\nRichie, on appeal front the Jeff r\nson County Circuit Court, ha; i>ce>:\n.tiled in the Supreme Court at I it\nj tie Hock. Richie was charged v\\ rit\ni having made remarks reflecting up\non tiie character of Bertha Kelley,\nSuit was brought, in the Jefferson\nCounty Circuit. Court with th con\nsent of the woman, the .jury return\nin.g a verdict of guilty and assess\ni ing his punishment at three year;\nin the penitentiary, whereupon the\ndefendant took an appeal to the\nSupreme Court.\niiioni of two billions and u half of dol\nlars and that directly and indirectly\nwe employed one million men, who in\nturn supported six million people, rep\nresenting one-fourth of the entire pop\nulation of the United States, L en\ndeavored to make it plain to them that\nin order to get any satisfaction or at\nleast consideration from the so-called\nprohibition party, we must obey the\nlaws.\n\u201cThe local leagues will form a State\norganization which will work for the\nenactment of the Model License Law\nin this State. This law provides,\namong other things, that the saloons\nshall be removed from politics abso\nlutely, that every license shall renew\nitself each year automatically and that\nthe proportion of licenses granted shall\nnot be greater than one for every five\nhundred populaton. This would mean\nin your city that you could not get\nanother cense here for several years,\naiding largely in making your license\nbecome a valuable asset and even bet\ntor than a life insurance policy, be\ncause your license would be perpetual.\nThe sum and substance of the Model\nLicense League is that we propose to\nmake it. more profitable for the saloon\nkeeper to obey the laws than it would\nbe for him to disobey them]. When\nwe have worked this out we have\nsolved the liquor problem.\n\"The press and a large number of\nfar-sighted, reasoning men of nation\nal reputation have not only endorsed\nthis movement, but are working teeth\nand nail in its behalf. Why, only on\nSaturday 'last Cardinal Gibbons is\nquoted in a New Orleans paper as\npractically advocating the proposition.\nWhen such men of broad minds give\nthis movement thought it shows that\nwe have struck a popular chord in\nthe minds of that element which we\nknow would always give any reason\nable proposition fair consideration,\u201d\nMr. Hutson leaves this morning for\n[Little Rock, where he will make ar\nrangements for a State convention to\nbe held in that city. The Pine Bluff\nModel License League is the first to\nbe organized in this State. Promi\nnent speakers will come to this city\nin the near future to openly discuss\nthe model' license law and to enthuse\ninterest in the movement.\nSETTLES WITH THE\nIRON MOUNTAIN\nControversy at McGehee, the Divis\nion Headquarters, Ts Believed to\nHave Come to an End\u2014A. Mc\nGehee Still in St. Louis.\nAfter several days, a settlement\nhas been reached between Abner\nMcGehee and the Iron Mountain\nmanagement at St. Louis, in regard\nto the action of the road in fencing\nin a strip of land in the heart of\nMcGehee, headquarters of the Val\nley division. Certain conditions\nhave bt en named in the settlement\nthat have not. yet been made known.\nMr. McGehee is still in St. Louis.\nMayor Baker of McGehee stated\nlast night that no news of the set\ntlement had yet. reached there, and\nthat the situation is practically un\nchanged.\nThe order to fence in tilt strip is\nsaid to have been issued from the\noffice of General Manager Sullivan\nin St. Louis.\nSHCHIEF'S SALE.\nBy virtue of a decree rendered\nin the chancery court of Jefferson\ncounty, 1 am directed by the clerk ol\nsaid court to offer for sale in front\nof the Court House, at Pine Bluff\nJefferson county, Ark., on\nMONDAY. THE 9 th DAY OF\nMARCH, 1908,\nbetween the hours prescribed bj\nlaw for judicial sales, to the highesi\nbidder on a credit of three month\nwith interest, the purchaser giving\nbond to secure purchase money, al\nthe right, title and interest of W\nL. Miller Co. in the following\ndescribed property, to wit:\nOne set of bar fixtures and sto\nof liquors, wines, etc., as per in\nventory on file in my office, lovi\non by me under an attachment a\nthe property of W. L. Miller S: Co\nto satisfy notes in favor of the Ar\nrow Distilling Company for f u\nhundred and sixty-two dollars am\ntwenty-two cents ($402,221 with in\nterest and costs.\nC. M. PHILPOT,\n2-1 4-21 Sheriff.\nFor One Night Only, Friday, February 21\nFirst time in Pine Bluff of greatest dramatic success of moddrn times\nFree List Suspended.\ngfr ,l\"\nHENRY B. HARRIS Presents\nTHE LION AND THE MOUSE\nBy CHARLES KLEIN\nA Cast of Distinguished Players\nTHE RFX\u2019.OttD -Two years i i New York; Six mouth in Chicago; Four\nmonths in Boston.\nMAY AND JULY\nUP ON FLURRY\nSlight Advance on New York Mar\nket Results in No Permanent\nBusiness\u2014Heavy Dry Goods Pur\nchases Indicates Improved Spring\nBusiness.\nNew York, Keb. 13.\u2014The market\nfluctuated most narrowly during the\nmorning session. The opening was\nslightly lower on the active months.\nA flurry of covering sent .May up to\n11.12 and July to 10.71. But there\nwas no evidence that any new7 busi\nness resulted. Sentiment among\nroom traders was bearish on the\npassage of anti-option law In .Mis\nsissippi. Liverpool ruled steady but\nthere was little English buying. The\nrally in cotton wras as much on ac\ncount of the strength in stocks as\non any local development. Easier\nprices prevailed after the morning\nbulge but the lack of both outside\nand professional business character\nized the session. There is a dis\ntinct change in the local dry goods\nsituation, buyers are more numer\nous and there is an expectation of\nimproved spring business. The sit\nuation from a speculative point of\nview is very much mixed but we\nthink the final outcome will result\nin lower prices. BACHE.\nNew Orleans Letter.\nNew Orleans, Feb. 13.\u2014Spot\nprices in Lierpool are 3 lower and\ndull, the turn-over is small, total\nsales only 6,000 bales. Futures\nseem dull, and trading without spe\ncial motive power. Our markets\nare in the same position. Leading\ninterests in the near positions in\nNew York do not appear ready yet\nfor a decided move. Large dis\ncounts under spot quotations are\nagainst selling of contracts and un\nfavorable outside considerations are\nagainst buying. New-erop factors\nare as yet too indefinite to attract\ntrading and business therefore is\nvery quiet all round. Parties hold\ning the long end of the March and\nMay deals in New York are sending\nvery bullish advices but this does\nlittle more than put traders on their\nguard.\nThe spot market is dull. Some\nscattered business in extras and to\nfill up shipments, but. no new de\nmand. Lower to sell.\nHAYWARD, VICK CLARK.\n\u2014Mrs. Alex Lazarus yesterday re\nceived the sad intelligence of th\ndeath of her sister, Miss Henri.\u2022ua\nMorris, which occurrei in Eui\\ po\nseveral days ago.\nPaid on Savings Deposits\nCompounded Semiannually\nOpen an Account Today\n\nCOTTON BELT SAVINGS\nTRUST CO.\n106 West Barraque St.\nPine Bluff, Ark\ni\u2014~ mnimn\nBACK GITES OUT,\nPlenty of Pine Bluff Readers Have\nThis Experience.\nYou tax the kidneys\u2014ovei work\nthem\u2014\nThey can't keep up the continual\nstrain.\nThe back gives out\u2014it aches and\npains;\nUrinary troubles set in.\nDon\u2019t wait longer\u